¬†@SC O'Dubhlaoch¬† the problem is not cars. If I remember correctly automotives in general (cars, airplanes, trains, boats and such) account for less than 10% of the global CO2 emissions. The other 90% is poor life choices for people and poorly engineered industry standards for animal raising, goods production and energy production.

To put it simple, the problem is not your car, the problem is that you stuff your face with fucking hamburgers every day, you don't turn the AC off when it's not needed, you buy shit tons of stuff that you don't need and your house insulation is a fucking joke. The simple solution would be stop eating mass produced meat and, instead, choosing meat from well raised animals (you'll pay the meat five times more and you'll not be able to afford eating meat everyday, but who gives a fuck: it's tastier and you'll avoid cancer and heart failure at 50 more easily), stop using electricity unless is stricly necessary (a little hot in the summer or a little cold in the winter is no biggie frankly), choose your house windows in a way the heat and the cold stays inside when needed without drafts and stuff like that and stop wasting so fucking much in general: repair your stuff or buy used instead of buying new, don't be a bitch and stop wasting money on new clothes every fucking week, learn how to repair your computer or your phone and live a more thrifty life.

On the other hand, of course industry has to do its own to contribute, like choosing renewable energy sources instead of choosing coal or oil (it's gonna cost a lot more to produce but who gives a fuck: raise your prices and make more durable stuff), being more respectful of what you make (a phone manifacturer, unless its Apple, doesn't care if their devices last two years and then they become slow and the battery dies: more phones sold equals more money) and, in general, lowering the production (if you sell less you're gonna produce less, that's logic).

Simple, right? Not only this way of life would be less toxic for our minds and we could really focus on what's important, but it could be beneficial to the world too. Of course the zero emission mark would not be obtainable, but just implementing the stuff I said would be a giant step towards it. But why we don't do that? I'll tell you why: people are fucking lazy and industry owners are greedy. Same old story.

Oh yeah, and since you claim you will listen to virtuous people only:
- I am a programmer and I know how to fix nearly everything if it breakes (laptops, desktops, phones, radios, TVs, consoles, what have you);
- I have my own garden (right now is tomatoes, onions, lettuce, cucumber, carrots and eggplant season);
- I eat good meat once or twice a week (the meat comes from my butcher that has cows, pigs, chickens, rabbits and horses in a farm 2 miles from my house);
- my newest clothes are 1 year old (except shoes and coats: the shoes last me two months or so because I walk a lot, and my coats are 10+ years old)
- I have a crapload of solar panels on my roof and my house is insulated (walls are made of mud, straw and stone and are 2 feet wide so heat and cold don't go needlessly outside);
- I turn on the AC more or less one month per year (in the summer we have 110+ degrees here);
-  I take the bike for less than 4 miles (my bike has 30 years old, it belonged to my grandfather, and I periodically fix it);
- I prefer the bus or the train to get places since I don't have an electric mean of transportation.
Now take me seriously.

